Visualizing uncertainty about LGBT poverty

Connor Gilroy

2019-10-28

M.V. Lee Badgett, Soon Kyu Choi, and Bianca D.M. Wilson released a report for the Williams Institute about LGBT poverty in the United States. They used data from the Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS), a major state-by-state health-related survey, to derive population estimates about LGBT and cis-straight poverty rates.

Using the 95% confidence intervals from p.39 of the report, I added error bars to Figure 2 on p.8:

I also tried confidence strips, using Claus Wilke’s ungeviz package:

My sense is that this better conveys the feeling of uncertainty and how that differs between groups, but others just found it confusing.

More ideas and examples can be found in Chapter 16, “Visualizing Uncertainty,” of his book on data visualization.

The code and data for this project can be found in this GitHub repository.
